---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

const title = "Import from Todoist to Pikos";
const description = "Move your Todoist projects into Pikos. Tasks, due dates, priorities, sub-tasks, and labels all come across via CSV.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>

  <main class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-8 py-20">

    <a href="/import" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-neutral-400 transition-colors hover:text-primary-500 dark:text-neutral-500 dark:hover:text-primary-400">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m15 18-6-6 6-6"/></svg>
      Import
    </a>

    <article>
      <h1 class="mt-8 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-50">Import from Todoist</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-neutral-400 dark:text-neutral-500">Export each project as CSV, then drop the file into Pikos.</p>

      <div class="prose mt-10 text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-300">

        <p>
          Todoist exports per-project CSV files from its web app. Pikos auto-detects the format from the headers and maps everything in place — sub-tasks, due dates, priorities, labels, and the notes attached to each task.
        </p>

        <h2>1. Export from Todoist</h2>

        <p>
          In Todoist, open a project. Click the project name in the breadcrumb (or the &hellip; menu, depending on the layout) and choose <strong>Export &rarr; Export as CSV</strong>. Todoist downloads a file named after the project.
        </p>

        <p>
          Repeat for each project you want to bring across. Todoist doesn't export everything in a single archive, so you'll end up with one CSV per project. That's fine — you'll import them one at a time.
        </p>

        <h2>2. Import in Pikos</h2>

        <p>
          Open Settings (<code>Cmd+,</code>), go to the <strong>Data</strong> tab, and click <strong>Select File</strong> next to "CSV". Pick the CSV you exported.
        </p>

        <p>
          Pikos reads the headers, recognizes the Todoist format, and pre-fills the column mappings for you. The mapping screen lets you confirm or override each column before anything is written.
        </p>

        <h2>3. Confirm the mapping, then preview</h2>

        <p>
          Click through to the preview. Review the list of pages that will be created, the folder they'll land in, and any warnings. The preview shows the same view you'll see after import, so what you see is what you'll get.
        </p>

        <p>
          Hit <strong>Import</strong> and you're done. Repeat for each project CSV.
        </p>

        <h2>What comes across</h2>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Tasks</strong> — each task becomes a Pikos page.</li>
          <li><strong>Notes</strong> — task comments are merged into the page body so you don't lose context.</li>
          <li><strong>Sub-tasks</strong> — Todoist's parent / child relationships are reconstructed in Pikos using its own page-parent model.</li>
          <li><strong>Due dates</strong> — both fixed dates and natural-language phrasing ("today at 11:00", "every Monday") are parsed where possible. Recurring rules become a single scheduled date for now; recurrence rules are on the way.</li>
          <li><strong>Priorities</strong> — Todoist's P1–P4 maps to Pikos's Urgent / High / Medium / Low.</li>
          <li><strong>Labels</strong> — become Pikos tags.</li>
          <li><strong>Project name</strong> — becomes the folder for the imported pages.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What doesn't come across</h2>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sections</strong> — Todoist sections within a project don't have a Pikos equivalent. Section names are preserved as a tag on each task in that section, so you can filter by them.</li>
          <li><strong>Reminders</strong> — Todoist doesn't include reminder times in the CSV export. Re-add critical ones in Pikos.</li>
          <li><strong>Filters and saved views</strong> — these are query definitions, not data; they don't transfer.</li>
          <li><strong>Karma, history, activity log</strong> — completion timestamps are preserved on each task, but the historical streak data isn't.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>If something goes sideways</h2>

        <p>
          Imports are reversible. Pikos snapshots the database first, every imported page is tagged with the import batch, and Settings &rarr; Data &rarr; "Undo last import" removes the lot. You can re-export from Todoist and try again with no leftovers.
        </p>

        <p>
          Ready to try? <a href="/download">Download Pikos</a> — the CSV importer is in the Data tab.
        </p>

      </div>
    </article>

  </main>

  <Footer current="/import/todoist" />
</Base>

<style>

  .prose :global(h2) {
    padding-top: 1rem;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-neutral-900);
  }
  :global(html.dark) .prose :global(h2) {
    color: var(--color-neutral-100);
  }

  .prose :global(p) {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }

  .prose :global(ul) {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    list-style-type: disc;
  }

  .prose :global(li) {
    margin-top: 0.375rem;
  }

  .prose :global(a) {
    color: var(--color-primary-500);
  }
  :global(html.dark) .prose :global(a) {
    color: var(--color-primary-400);
  }
  .prose :global(a:hover) {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .prose :global(code) {
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    background-color: var(--color-neutral-150);
    padding: 0.125rem 0.375rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }
  :global(html.dark) .prose :global(code) {
    background-color: var(--color-neutral-800);
  }
</style>
